The neon glow of the Memory Exchange hummed just beyond the cracked pavement of the alley, its holographic sign flickering like a dying star—*Memories: The Most Valuable Currency*. Elias had walked past it a dozen times before, his fingers twitching at the thought of what lay within. Tonight, though, he stood beneath it, the cold metal of the doorframe biting into his palms. The air smelled of ozone and something older, something like rusted hope.

He wasn’t here for the usual trade—no stolen moments from tourists, no fleeting joys sold by those who couldn’t afford to keep them. Elias wanted something else. Something that had been gnawing at him for months.

The exchange was a low-slung building, its exterior a patchwork of solar panels and graffiti that had long since faded into something unreadable. The entrance was flanked by two figures in black suits, their faces obscured by the dim light. One of them stepped forward, his voice a low rasp. *"Evening. What can we do for you?"*

Elias exhaled, his breath fogging in the cool night air. "I need something specific."

The man’s eyes narrowed. "Specificity has a price."

"I know." Elias reached into his coat and pulled out a small, sealed vial. Inside, the liquid shimmered with a faint, sickly blue light. "This is mine. All of it."

The guard hesitated, then gestured for Elias to follow. Inside, the exchange was a cavernous space, its high ceiling lined with flickering screens displaying the latest transactions—*A first kiss, 1200 credits. A mother’s laughter, 800. A deathbed confession, 5000.* The air smelled of antiseptic and something sweet, like overripe fruit.

At the center of the room stood a woman in a sleek, form-fitting bodysuit, her dark hair pulled into a severe bun. Her name was Dr. Veyra Kael, and she was the exchange’s curator, the one who decided what could be bought, sold, or destroyed. She looked up as Elias approached, her sharp eyes taking in the vial in his hand.

"You’ve brought us a memory," she said, her voice smooth, almost amused. "A rare one, I’d wager."

Elias didn’t answer. He set the vial on the counter between them. Inside, the blue light pulsed, and for a moment, he could almost feel it—the weight of it, the way it had clung to him like a second skin.

Dr. Kael picked it up, her fingers brushing against the glass. "This isn’t just any memory. It’s *his*."

Elias’s jaw tightened. "Yes."

She turned the vial so the light caught it just right, and for a second, Elias saw it—the way it had looked when it was still inside him. A man’s face, young, his skin marked with the scars of a war he’d never talked about. A voice, rough with the weight of too many years, whispering something in a language Elias didn’t understand. And then—pain. Not just physical, but something deeper, something that had festered inside him until it became a part of him, a shadow he couldn’t shake.

Dr. Kael set the vial down. "You’re selling him."

Elias’s hands clenched. "I’m not selling him. I’m freeing him."

She studied him for a long moment. "Freedom has a cost."

"I know what it costs." Elias’s voice was quiet, but there was steel beneath it. "I’ve been paying for it my whole life."

Dr. Kael sighed, as if she were tired of the same argument over and over. "Very well. But you understand the terms. Once this memory is transferred, it’s gone. There’s no recall. No undoing."

Elias nodded. "I understand."

She reached for a terminal, her fingers flying over the surface. A holographic interface flickered to life, displaying a contract. Elias read it quickly—standard terms, but with a clause at the bottom that made his stomach twist. *"The seller acknowledges full responsibility for any emotional or psychological consequences resulting from the transfer."* He signed it with a flick of his wrist, his thumbprint sealing the deal.

Dr. Kael placed the vial into a slot in the terminal. The machine whirred to life, and the blue light inside began to shift, to *move*, as if the memory itself was struggling against the transfer. Elias closed his eyes, gripping the edge of the counter until his knuckles turned white.

Then—silence.

When he opened his eyes, the vial was empty. The blue light was gone.

Dr. Kael picked up a small, metallic case from the counter. Inside was a single, thin strip of something that looked like a credit chip. She handed it to Elias. "This is your payment. It contains the memory of the transfer. You’ll need it if you ever want to reclaim what you’ve given."

Elias took it, his fingers brushing against the cold metal. "I won’t need it."

She raised an eyebrow. "Why not?"

He looked at her, really looked at her for the first time. "Because I don’t want to remember this."

Dr. Kael studied him for a long moment, then nodded. "As you wish."

Elias left the exchange without another word. The alley was darker now, the neon glow of the Memory Exchange casting long shadows that seemed to stretch and twist like living things. He walked home, his steps slow, his mind a blank space where the memory had once been.

He didn’t know what he’d expected. Maybe relief. Maybe regret. But what he felt was something else—something lighter, something almost like freedom.

He thought about the man in the memory—the one he’d never met, the one he’d never even known existed until now. A soldier, he’d been told. A man who had carried something inside him that had broken him, piece by piece, until there was nothing left but the memory of it.

Elias had carried that memory for years. He’d been born with it, a genetic anomaly, a piece of someone else’s past that had been woven into his own DNA. He didn’t remember the man’s name. He didn’t remember the war. He didn’t remember much of anything beyond the pain, the way it had shaped him, the way it had made him who he was.

And now it was gone.

He stopped walking, standing in the middle of the alley, the cold night air wrapping around him like a shroud. He thought about the people who had bought and sold memories before him—the ones who had traded their joys for credits, their sorrows for a little peace. He thought about the ones who had sold their own memories, the ones who had looked into the terminal and seen the light flicker out, just like his had.

And he thought about the man in the memory—the one who had been a stranger to him, but who had been a part of him all the same.

Elias didn’t know if he was happy. He didn’t know if he was sad. He just knew that the weight he’d carried for so long was gone, and that made him feel both lighter and heavier than he’d ever been before.

He turned and walked away from the alley, away from the Memory Exchange, away from the past he’d just left behind. He didn’t know where he was going. He didn’t know what he was going to do.

But for the first time in his life, he felt like he might have a choice.

